# Premises:
# The cost of the GRE test is $205.
Cost(GRE, 205USD).

# ETS provides financial aid to GRE applicants who prove economic hardship.
# The original logic implies that if someone is a GRE applicant AND has economic hardship, THEN ETS provides financial aid.
# We are making the condition explicit: FinancialAid is provided *to* the applicant.
∀x (GREApplicant(x) ∧ EconomicHardship(x) → Provides(ETS, FinancialAid, x)).

# Economic hardship is defined as a difficulty caused by having too little money or too few resources.
# The original logic uses a bi-conditional (↔) which is appropriate.
# The Predicates are used to construct this definition, so we need to ensure the instances are correctly tied.
∀eh (EconomicHardship(eh) ↔ (Difficulty(eh) ∧ (CausedBy(eh, HavingTooLittleMoney) ∨ CausedBy(eh, HavingTooFewResources)))).

Person(Tom).

# Tom lives in a single-parent family.
LivesIn(Tom, SingleParentFamily).

∃d (Dad(d, Tom) ∧ OutOfWork(d, >1 Year)).

# Duration(d, >1 Year) ∧ OutOfWork(d, >1 Year) → OutOfWork(d, >1 Year). - This is also a tautology.
